record_data.record_plain_text: PORTLAND GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF FIRST REVISED VOLUME NO. 13 PORTLAND GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF FIRST REVISED VOLUME NO. 13 RATE SCHEDULE FOR THE SALE OF ANCILLARY SERVICES AT COST BASED RATES 1.0 DEFINITIONS 1.1 Ancillary Services: Those services that are necessary to support the transmission of capacity and energy from resources to loads while maintaining reliable operation of the transmission system in accordance with Good Utility Practice 1.2 Commission: The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.3 Customer: Any person that executes an Umbrella Service Agreement for service under this tariff. 1.4 Open Access Transmission Tariff: Portland General Electric Company's (PGE) Commission approved transmission tariff for non-discriminatory service. 1.5 Regulation and Frequency Response Service: A power capacity service that is similar to the Ancillary Service of the same name provided under PGE's Open Access Transmission Tariff, except that service under this Rate Schedule will be available only with transactions where the Customer is not receiving basic transmission service under PGE's Open Access Transmission tariff. Descriptions of this service and the rates and/or methodology are included in Appendix 1. 1.6 Operating Reserves - Spinning Reserves: A power capacity service that is similar to the Ancillary Service of the same name provided under PGE's Open Access Transmission Tariff, except that service under this Rate Schedule will be available only where the Customer is not receiving basic transmission service under PGE's Open Access Transmission Tariff. Descriptions of this service and the rates and/or methodology are included in Appendix 2. 1.7 Operating Reserves - Supplemental Reserves: A power capacity service that is similar to the Ancillary Service of the same name provided under PGE's Open Access Transmission Tariff, except that service under this Rate Schedule will be available only where the Customer is not receiving basic transmission service under PGE's Open Access Transmission tariff. Descriptions of this service and the rates and/or methodology are included in Appendix 3. 1.8 Transmission Function: Means those PGE employees whose responsibilities include the operation and control of facilities that are necessary to ensure the safe and reliable transfer of power across PGE's transmission facilities in interstate commerce. 1.9 Umbrella Service Agreement: The agreement and any amendments or supplements thereto entered into by Customer. 1.10 Wholesale Merchant Function or WMF: means those PGE employees whose responsibilities include sale for resale, or purchase for resale, of electric energy and Ancillary Services in interstate commerce and the resale, assignment or transfer of transmission rights obtained pursuant to a transmission service agreement to which PGE's Wholesale Merchant Function is a party. 2.0 General Purpose The purpose of this Rate Schedule is to provide for the sale of Ancillary Services by PGE's Wholesale Merchant Function at cost based rates to off -system wholesale purchasers. These Ancillary Services are separate and distinct from those provided by the Transmission Function. Ancillary Services available under this Rate Schedule include Spinning Reserves, Supplemental Reserves and Regulating Reserves. Service under this Rate Schedule is not available in conjunction with basic transmission services under PGE's Open Access Transmission Tariff Volume No. 8. 2.1 Rates The specific Ancillary Services, prices and/or compensation methods are described on the Schedules that are attached to and made a part of this Rate Schedule. Any offer of a discount made by PGE's Wholesale Merchant Function must be made available to all Customers eligible to take service under this Rate Schedule. A discount agreed upon for an Ancillary Service must be offered for the same period to all Customers eligible to take service under this Rate Schedule. This Rate Schedule shall become effective on the date the Federal Regulatory Energy Commission allows it to become effective. 2.2 Duration This Rate Schedule shall continue in effect until terminated or changed and such termination or change becomes effective in accordance with any applicable regulatory requirements. 2.3 Services To Be Provided 2.3.1 Regulation and Frequency Response Service: Wholesale Merchant Function shall provide this service at a rate not to exceed PGE's costs. Descriptions of this service and the rates and/or methodology are included in Schedule 1. 2.3.2 Operating Reserves - Spinning Reserves: Wholesale Merchant Function shall provide this service at a rate not to exceed PGE's costs. Descriptions of this service and the rates and/or methodology are included in Schedule 2. 2.3.3 Operating reserves - Supplemental Reserves: Wholesale Merchant Function shall provide this service at a rate not to exceed PGE's costs. Descriptions of this service and the rates and/or methodology are included in Schedule 3. 2.4. Term of Service The Ancillary Services will be available on an hourly, daily, weekly, monthly or an annual basis. 2.5 Non-Discrimination Wholesale Merchant Function will provide the Ancillary Services on a non-discriminatory and first-come, first-served basis. 2.6 Terms and Conditions As a condition to executing an Umbrella Service Agreement, WMF may require Customer to furnish its financial reports and reports to shareholders. Should the Customer's creditworthiness, financial responsibility, or performance viability be unsatisfactory to WMF, WMF may also require the Customer to provide, at the Customer's option, either (i) the posting of a letter of credit, (ii) a cash prepayment, (iii) a guarantee, or (iv) the posting of other acceptable collateral or security by the Customer. If the Customer fails to provide such satisfactory assurances of its ability to perform a transaction hereunder within three (3) business days of demand therefore, WMF (in addition to exercising any and all remedies available at law or in equity, expressly inclusive of, but not limited to withholding, setting off against or recouping from amounts otherwise due) (i) may suspend performance of the transaction, or (ii) immediately terminate the transaction, calculating, consistent with the Umbrella Service Agreement and any confirmation agreement, the amount of its costs, expenses, and losses incurred due to the Customer's inability to perform, and presenting the Customer with a demand therefore which must be paid within three (3) business days of receipt. In determining whether the Customer has provided satisfactory assurances and in determining the action to be taken, PGE may suspend performance or terminate the transaction without making a filing at FERC. This Section may be modified by agreement of the Parties in writing. 2.7 Compensations The Wholesale Merchant Function may sell Ancillary Services pursuant to this Rate Schedule to Customer at a price not to exceed the total of the price in PGE's Commission approved Open Access Transmission Tariff for similar services and the price provided under 2.3 above. 2.8 Billing and Payment 2.8.1 Billing Procedure: Within a reasonable time after the first day of each month, Wholesale Merchant Function shall submit an invoice to the Customer for the charges for all services furnished under this Rate Schedule during the preceding month. The invoices shall be paid by the Customer within twenty (20) days of receipt. All payments shall be made in immediately available funds payable to Wholesale Merchant Function, or by wire transfer to a bank account designated by Wholesale Merchant Function. 2.8.2 Interest on Unpaid Balances: Interest on any unpaid amounts shall be calculated in accordance with the methodology specified for interest on refunds in the Commission's regulations at 18 C.F.R. section 35.19(a) (2) (iii). Interest on delinquent amounts shall be calculated from the due date of the bill to the date of payment. When payments are made by mail, bills shall be considered as having been paid on the date of receipt by Wholesale Merchant Function. 2.8.3 Customer Default: Except in the case of a good faith billing dispute, if Customer fails to pay an invoice in full by the due date, and such failure is not corrected within thirty (30) calendar days, Customer shall be in default of its obligations under this Rate Schedule and the Umbrella Service Agreement. In the event of default, Wholesale Merchant Function may cease providing Ancillary Services to Customer without additional approval from the Commission or any other regulatory governmental body. Prior to ceasing services pursuant to this Section 2.8.3, Wholesale Merchant Function shall provide, via electronic means, two business days notice of such termination of services. 2.9 Modifications PGE may unilaterally apply to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this Rate Schedule under section 205 of the Federal Power Act and the regulations promulgated under that Act. 3.0 Other Terms and Conditions 3.1 Market Behavior Rules As a condition to sell ancillary services at cost-based rates, Portland General Electric Company (hereafter, Seller) will comply with the following market Behavior Rules: 1. Unit Operation: Seller will operate and schedule generating facilities, undertake maintenance, declare outages and commit or otherwise bid supply in a manner that complies with the Commission-approved rules and regulations of the applicable power market. Compliance with this Market Behavior Rule does not require Seller to bid or supply electric energy or other electricity products unless such requirement is a part of a separate Commission approves tariff or requirement applicable to Seller 2. Market Manipulation: Actions or transactions that are without a legitimate business purpose and that are intended to or foreseeably could manipulate market prices, market conditions, or market rules for electric energy or electricity products are prohibited. Actions or transactions undertaken by Seller that are explicitly contemplated in Commission-approved rules and regulations of an applicable power market (such as virtual supply or load bidding) or taken at the directions of an ISO or RTO are not in violation of this Market Behavior Rule. Prohibited actions and transactions include, but are not limited to: a. pre-arranged offsetting trades of the same product among the same parties which involve no economic risk and no net change in beneficial ownership (sometimes called "wash trades"); b. transactions predicated on submitting false information to transmission providers or other entities responsible for operation of the transmission grid (such as inaccurate load or generation data; or scheduling non-firm service or products sold as firm), unless Seller exercised due diligence to prevent such occurrences; c. transactions in which an entity first creates artificial congestions and then purports to relieve such artificial congestions (unless Seller exercised due diligence to prevent such occurrence); and d. collusion with another party for the purpose of manipulating market prices, market conditions, or market rules for electric energy or electricity products 3. Communications: Seller will provide accurate and factual information and not submit false or misleading information, or omit material information, in any communication with the Commission, Commission-approved market monitors, Commission-approved regional transmission organizations, or Commission-approved independent system operators, or jurisdictional transmission providers, unless Seller exercised due diligence to prevent such occurrences. 4. Reporting: To the extent Seller engages in reporting of transactions to publishers of electricity or natural gas price indices, Seller shall provide accurate and factual information, and not knowingly submit false or misleading information or omit material information to any such publisher, by reporting its transactions in a manner consistent with the procedures set forth in the Policy Statement issued by the Commission in Docket No. PL03-3 and any clarification thereto. Seller shall notify the Commission of whether it engages in such reporting of its transactions and update the Commission by submitting information accurately in the Contract Section of the Electric Quarterly Report (EQR). In addition, Seller shall adhere to such other standards and requirements for price reporting as the Commission may order. 5. Record Retention: Seller shall retain, for a period of five years, all data and information upon which it billed the prices it charged for the electric energy or electric energy products it sold pursuant to this tariff or the prices it reported for use in price indices. 6. Related Tariffs: Seller shall not violate or collude with another party in actions that violate Seller's market-based rate code of conduct or Order No. 889 standards of conduct, as they may be revised from time to time. Any violation of these Market Behavior Rules will constitute a tariff violation. Seller will be subject to disgorgement of unjust profits associated with the tariff violation, from the date on which the tariff violation occurred. Seller may also be subject to suspension or revocation of its authority to sell at market-based rates or other appropriate non-monetary penalties. Portland General Electric Company Form of Umbrella Service Agreement For the Sale of Ancillary Services This Service Agreement, dated as of , is entered into, by and between Portland General Electric Company ("PGE") and ("Customer"). PGE and Customer may also be referred to collectively as "Parties," and individually as "Party." PGE agrees to furnish and Customer agrees to purchase Ancillary Services pursuant to the terms and conditions of PGE's Rate Schedule for the Sale of Ancillary Services as revised from time to time pursuant to filings with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.0 Customer has been determined by PGE to be an eligible customer under the Rate Schedule. 2.0 This Service Agreement shall extend for from the date hereof, and shall continue in force thereafter until and unless canceled upon a minimum of 60 days prior written notice by one Party to the other Party. However, sales already entered into prior to notice of termination shall continue for the duration of the sale. 3.0 The type of Ancillary Services to be provided by PGE hereunder may be: Spinning Reserves, Supplemental Reserves and Regulating Reserves. At the time of entering into a sale of Ancillary Services the Parties shall identify and document the agreed to type(s) of Ancillary Services to be provided there under. 4.0 For each transaction, Customer shall pay to PGE such charges as are agreed upon between the Parties, orally, or, if expressly required by either Party with respect to a particular transaction, in writing, provided however that such charge shall not exceed PGE's costs. Each Party consents to the recording of all telephone conversations relating to transactions under this Service Agreement between its trading and marketing employees and the trading and marketing employees of the other Party, and that any such recordings will be retained in confidence, secured from improper access, and may be submitted in evidence in any proceeding or action relating to this agreement. With respect to such recordings, each Party waives any further notice of such monitoring or recording, and agrees to notify its employees of such monitoring or recording and to obtain any necessary consent of such employees. The recording, and the terms and conditions described therein, shall be the controlling evidence of the Parties' agreement with respect to a particular transaction. 5.0 Any notice made to or by a Party regarding this Service Agreement shall be made to the representative of the other Party as indicated below. PORTLAND GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY: By: Date: ______________________ Printed Name: Title: _______________________________________ CUSTOMER: By: Date: ______________________ Printed Name: Title: _______________________________________ SCHEDULE 1 Regulation and Frequency Response Service Regulation and Frequency Response Service is necessary to provide for the continuous balancing of resources (generation and interchange) with load and for maintaining scheduled interconnection frequency at sixty cycles per second (60 Hz). Regulation and Frequency Response Service is accomplished by committing on-line generation whose output is raised or lowered (predominantly through the use of automatic generating control equipment) as necessary to follow the moment-by-moment changes in load. The charges for Regulation and Frequency Response Service are set forth below. The rate for long-term Regulation and Frequency Response Service shall be up to $6.695 per kW per month. The rate for short-term weekly Regulation and Frequency Response Service shall be up to $1.545 per kW-week. The rate for short-term on-peak Regulation and Frequency Response Service shall be up to $0.257 per kW-day. The rate for short-term off-peak Regulation and Frequency Response Service shall be up to $0.221 per kW-day. Hourly rates for Regulation and Frequency Response Service shall be up to $16.09/ MWh for on-peak service and up to $9.17/ MWh for off-peak service. The peak period for daily service shall be all hours Monday through Saturday, excluding WECC holidays. The peak period for hourly service shall be the sixteen hours from 6:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m., Monday through Saturday, excluding WECC holidays. The total demand charge in any week, pursuant to a reservation for Daily delivery, shall not exceed the weekly rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any day during such week. The total demand charge in any day, pursuant to a reservation for Hourly delivery, shall not exceed the daily rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour during such day. In addition, the total demand charge in any week, pursuant to a reservation for Hourly or Daily delivery, shall not exceed the weekly rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour during such week. SCHEDULE 2 Operating Reserve - Spinning Reserve Service Spinning Reserve Service is needed to serve load immediately in the event of a system contingency. Spinning Reserve Service may be provided by generating units that are on-line and loaded at less than maximum output. The charges for Spinning Reserve Service are set forth below. The rate for long-term Spinning Reserve Service shall be up to $6.695 per kW-month. The rate for short-term weekly Spinning Reserve Service shall be up to $1.545 per kW-week. The rate for short-term on-peak Spinning Reserve Service shall be up to $0.257 per kW-day. The rate for short-term off-peak Spinning Reserve Service shall be up to $0.221 per kW-day. Hourly rates for Spinning Reserve Service shall be up to $16.09/ MWh for on-peak service and up to $9.17/ MWh for off-peak service. The peak period for daily service shall be all hours Monday through Saturday, excluding WECC holidays. The peak period for hourly service shall be the sixteen hours from 6:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m., Monday through Saturday, excluding WECC holidays. The total demand charge in any week, pursuant to a reservation for Daily delivery, shall not exceed the weekly rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any day during such week. The total demand charge in any day, pursuant to a reservation for Hourly delivery, shall not exceed the daily rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour during such day. In addition, the total demand charge in any week, pursuant to a reservation for Hourly or Daily delivery, shall not exceed the weekly rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour during such week. SCHEDULE 3 Operating Reserve - Supplemental Reserve Service Supplemental Reserve Service is needed to serve load in the event of a system contingency; however, it is not available immediately to serve load but rather within a short period of time. Supplemental Reserve Service may be provided by generating units that are on-line but unloaded, by quick-start generation or by interruptible load. The charges for Supplemental Reserve Service are set forth below. The rate for long-term Supplemental Reserve Service shall be up to $6.695 per kW- month. The rate for short-term weekly Supplemental Reserve Service shall be up to $1.545 per kW - week. The rate for short-term on-peak Supplemental Reserve Service shall be up to $0.257 per kW-day. The rate for short-term off-peak Supplemental Reserve Service shall be up to $0.221 per kW-day. Hourly rates for Supplemental Reserve Service shall be up to $16.09/MWh for on-peak service and up to $9.17/MWh for off-peak service. The peak period for daily service shall be all hours Monday through Saturday, excluding WECC holidays. The peak period for hourly service shall be the sixteen hours from 6:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m., Monday through Saturday, excluding WECC holidays. The total demand charge in any week, pursuant to a reservation for Daily delivery, shall not exceed the weekly rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any day during such week. The total demand charge in any day, pursuant to a reservation for Hourly delivery, shall not exceed the daily rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour during such day. In addition, the total demand charge in any week, pursuant to a reservation for Hourly or Daily delivery, shall not exceed the weekly rate specified above times the highest amount in kilowatts of Reserved Capacity in any hour during such week.
